('HALIFAX PLANETARIUM AT DALHOUSIE UNIVERSITY', 'Special Events', '14.30', '2015-03-20', 'Some of the brightest stars visible are up in the constellations of the clear Winter-Spring night sky; this year Venus and Jupiter shine brightly amongst them. Come and learn where to find these objects and what makes them shine.\r\n\r\n\r\nCost\r\nAdmission: $5 (at the door); reductions for families (min. age 8 years)\r\n\r\nAdditional Information\r\nReservations required: go to astronomynovascotia.ca\r\nFollow the instructions and specify your show date and time.\r\n\r\nEach show is about an hour long. Full details will be sent before the show.\r\nPlease do not be late; no admission after the door closes.', 'Rm. 120, Dunn Bldg, Dalhousie University, 6310 Coburg Rd', 74),
('RACISM IS KILLING US SOFTLY BUT STILL WE ARISE: LESSONS LEARNED FROM AFRICAN CANADIAN ACTIVISTS', 'Lectures, Seminars', '16.00 - 20.00', '2015-03-20', 'The Black Student Advising Centre in conjunction with the School of Social Work, Association of Black Social Workers and the James Robinson Johnston (JRJ) chair presents poster presentations and discussion by Social Work Students. Facilitators are Dr. Wanda Thomas Bernard and Oluronke Taiwo\r\n\r\nCost\r\nFree\r\nAdditional Information\r\nCome out to join us to discuss this interesting lecture series in commemoration of the International Day for the Elimination of Racial Discrimination. Light Refreshments will be served.\r\n\r\nContact\r\nOluronke Taiwo \r\n(902) 494-2210 \r\ntaiwooa@dal.ca \r\nDr. Wanda Thomas Bernard \r\n(902) 494-1190 \r\nwanda.bernard@dal.ca', 'Room 303 Dalhousie Student Union Building (SUB)', 75),
