('DALHOUSIES BUDGETING PROCESS (HALIFAX)', 'Training & Professional Development', '21.00 - 22.30', '2015-03-23', 'This session will provide a general overview of the development of the University operating budget and will focus on the detailed budgeting process at the Faculty/Departmental level. Topics will include budget submissions, salary incrementation and budget adjustments. This session will focus on the operating budget funding.\r\n \r\nThis workshop is designed for anyone responsible for developing an office or departmental budget for submission to Financial Services. \r\nTo Register: https://events-eod.dal.ca/workshop.php?id=1031\r\n\r\nCost\r\nFree\r\nContact\r\neod@dal.ca', 'Room B400 in the Killam Library', 77),
('SENATE MEETING', 'Meetings', '16.00 - 18.00', '2015-03-23', 'Cost\r\nn/a\r\n\r\nContact\r\nAndrea Power, Associate Secretariat of Senate\r\nUniversity Secretariat, Tel. 902-494-3715 \r\nandrea.power@dal.ca', 'University Hall, Macdonald Building', 78),
('DALHOUSIES BUDGETING PROCESS (TRURO)', 'Training & Professional Development', '21.00', '2015-03-24', 'This session will provide a general overview of the development of the University operating budget and will focus on the detailed budgeting process at the Faculty/Departmental level. Topics will include budget submissions, salary incrementation and budget adjustments. This session will focus on the operating budget funding. \r\n\r\nThis workshop is designed for anyone responsible for developing an office or departmental budget for submission to Financial Services. \r\n\r\nTo Register: https://events-eod.dal.ca/workshop.php?id=1036', 'Cumming Hall, CA Douglas Room', 79),
('ESL WORKSHOP: FLOW AND COHESION', 'Workshops', '16.00 - 18.00', '2015-03-24', 'Good academic writing is not just a series of disconnected ideas; it shows unity and flows within and between paragraphs. In this workshop you will look at the structures and vocabulary needed to take your academic writing from good to great.\r\n\r\nCost\r\nFree', 'Mona Campbell Building Room 1110', 80),
('SILENCING THE ACADEMY: ACADEMIC FREEDOM AND THE FUTURE OF UNIVERSITY GOVERNANCE', 'Lectures, Seminars', '19.30 - 21.30', '2015-03-24', 'Panel discussion on the role of faculty in university decision-making and its link to academic freedom. Panelists: Dr. James L. Turk, Dr. Letitia Meynell, Dr. Victor Catano. Moderated by Dr. Catrina Brown. Sponsored by the Dalhousie Faculty Association.\r\n\r\nCost\r\nFree\r\nAdditional Information\r\nhttp://dfa.ns.ca/news_items/save-the-date-tuesday-march-24-silencing-the-academy-academic-freedom-and-the-future-of-university-governance\r\n\r\nContact\r\ncommunications@dfa.ns.ca', 'Rm 303 Student Union Building', 81),
('INTERNATIONAL PERSPECTIVES ON SCIENCE AND ECONOMICS: STUDENT CONFERENCE 2015', 'Conferences', '12.30 - 15.30', '2015-03-25', 'Join the 3rd year students in Dalhousie’s China Program in Economics and students from the Science without Borders initiative with Brazil as they give their perspective on such areas as policy matters, international trade, sustainable development, consumer behaviours and interesting topics on science and engineering.\r\n\r\nCost\r\nFree\r\nAdditional Information\r\nOpening addresses by: \r\n\r\nDr. Fiona Black, Associate Vice President, Academic \r\nDr. Bruce Smith, Professor, Dept. of Mathematics and Statistics \r\nDr. Kuan Xu, Chair, Dept. of Economics\r\n\r\nLight refreshments will be served.\r\n\r\nContact\r\nwww.dal.ca/esl or call: 494-8062\r\n\r\n', 'Mona Campbell Building (Rooms 1110, 1111, 3110 and 3207)', 82),
('TEACHING, MODELLING AND ASSESSING PEOPLE SKILLS IN UNDERGRADUATE COURSES', 'Workshops', '14.00 -  15.30', '2015-03-25', 'Facilitator\r\nJill Marie McSweeney, IDPhD Candidate\r\nGraduate Teaching Associate\r\nCentre for Learning and Teaching\r\nDalhousie University\r\n\r\nInterpersonal communication includes skills we use daily to relate to each other. This broad set of skills includes being a good listener; not criticizing, condemning, or demeaning others; and trying to see situations and emotions from multiple points of view. While there is little doubt that these skills are important for employability and career success, as well as in personal relationships, they can be elusive in curriculum and be minimized as ‘people’ or ‘soft’ skills. How can we meaningfully incorporate this skill set into our courses and programs to enable students to recognize the value of developing them? How might we assess such skills? And, as importantly, how do we as educators appropriately model these behaviours in our interactions with our students that we are trying to promote? How do our own actions influence who our students become?\r\n', 'Killam Library, Room B400', 83),
