('BASICS OF WEB WRITING', 'Training & Professional Development', '10:00 - 12:00', '2015-04-07', 'Learn the basics of web writing by understanding how most of us read online compared to how we read in print. In this two-hour seminar, Lisa Holmes or Matt Semansky (Communications & Marketing / Web Team) will share insights from their work on the Dal website and training they received with international usability experts Nielsen Norman Group. \r\n\r\nFor more information: https://events-eod.dal.ca/workshop.php?id=1025', 'TBA', 112),
('AFRO-CUBAN JAZZ AND BEYOND WITH IGNACIO BERROA AND HILARIO DURAN', 'Concerts, Performances & Arts', 'Starts: Tuesday April 7, 2015 - 11:30 AM', '2015-04-07', 'AFRO-CUBAN JAZZ AND BEYOND, IGNACIO BERROA & HILARIO DURAN\r\nA series of clinics provides an historical view of the development of Afro-Cuban music, illuminating how the separate and distinct aspects of European and African contributions have combined to enrich the music world.\r\n\r\nSee the full series of events here: http://www.dal.ca/content/dam/dalhousie/pdf/faculty/arts/performing-arts/ACJaB%202015%20FSPA%20Schedule%20of%20Events.pdf', 'Details TBA', 113),
('HOW QRA IS USING CUTTING-EDGE COMPUTING TO FIND DESIGN FLAWS IN THE NEXT GENERATION OF COMPLEX MACHINES', 'Lectures, Seminars', 'Tuesday April 7, 2015 - 11:30 AM', '2015-04-07', 'The next generation of semiautonomous software-driven machines are bringing a new era of technological capability, allowing humanity to do things that were thought science ï¬ction just a few decades ago. The development of these machines is also bringing unprecedented levels of complexity we must learn to manage. Undetected errors due to the integration of multiple semiautonomous systems can lead to catastrophic outcomes, and the earlier and faster these errors are detected the lower the overall development costs and the more conï¬dence we can have on these machines. In this presentation we will talk about our current efforts at QRA to develop rigorous analysis software tools to verify and validate complex engineered systems, and we will also share our experience using advanced computing architectures, such as the D-Wave Two, in the analysis of aerospace systems. \r\n', 'Slonim Conference Room (#430), Goldberg Computer Science Building', 114),
('PUBLIC LECTURE: EBOLA AND COMPANY: THE ANIMAL SOURCES OF EMERGING VIRUSES, BY DR. DAVID QUAMMEN', 'Lectures, Seminars', 'Tuesday April 7, 2015 - 07:00 PM', '2015-04-07', 'A Free Public Lecture by David Quammen, an author and journalist whose twelve books include The Song of the Dodo, the Reluctant Mr. Darwin, and recently Spillover, on emerging diseases and short-listed for seven national and international awards. He has published in Harper, National Geographic, Outside, Esquire, the Atlantic, Rolling Stone, and The New York Times, been honored with an Academy Award from the American Academy of Arts and Letters, and is a three-time recipient of the National Magazine Award. He is a Contributing Writer for National Geographic, in whose service he travels often, usually to wild and remote places. His home is in Bozeman, Montana.', 'Theatre B, Tupper Medical Building Link, 5850 College Street', 115),
