('ENGINEERING ROBOT COMPETITION 2015', 'Exhibits and Displays', '10:00 AM', '2015-07-23', 'Nothing is worse than a plumbing disaster especially one that requires yu to fight mutant turtles cross lava and when you try to rescue your princess she often ends up being in another castle. To help with such plumbing disasters Dal Engineering students have designed autonomous robots that will fight on behalf of the plumber brothers giving them time to finally relax.', 'Sexton Campus Gymnasium', 155),
('HALIFAX PLANETARIUM AT DALHOUSIE UNIVERSITY DOWNTOWN MILKY WAY', 'Special Events', '07:15 PM', '2015-07-23', 'Come and learn the basic constellations that can be seen at this time of year. \r\nYou will also learn about the galaxy in which we live the Milky Way.\r\nOur sun is just one of about 300 billion stars that compose the Milky Way.\r\nWe are located out in the suburbs… if an alien asked you which way it was to the downtown could you direct them? You will after this show', 'Rm. 120 Dunn Bldg Dalhousie University 6310 Coburg Rd', 156),
('Using distributed word vector representation for text classification', 'Lectures Seminars', '03:30 PM', '2015-07-24', 'Distributed word vector representations have been shown to exhibit many interesting semantic and syntactic properties. Recently they have been successfully used in various word-based text mining tasks as named entity recognition and word associations. Text classification is a classic text mining problem which requires not only a useful word representation but also a representation for a sentence and a text. We have performed a series of experiments using an adapted word vector representation for short texts twits. The proposed model results in a dense vector and can take advantage of the additional unlabelled data if such data is available. We compare the performance of our model with the standard BOW text representation.', 'Slonim Room 430 Goldberg Computer Science Building', 157),
('CSGS Cup 2015', 'Athletics', '04:00 PM ', '2015-07-24', 'Last year''s match was a close one with Mona Campbell team beating Goldberg . Will Goldberg get it back in 2015 or will Mona Campbell sweep the cup again The field is booked. Join us on Friday June 19th at Dalhousie Wickwire field and bring your health card and student ID with you \r\n\r\nIf you are interested in enjoying this epic game of soccer between two CS giants and want to take a break from your computer send us an email ', 'Wickwire Field Dalhousie Universtiy', 158),
('Dalhousie at the Halifax Pride Parade', 'Special Events', '12:00 PM', '2015-07-25', 'Dalhousie is proud to be a part of the 28th annual Halifax Pride Parade on July 25th and we would love to have you march with us\r\n\r\nReady to walk. Please meet us at 2240 Valour Way around noon in order to meet up with the rest of the Dal contingent \r\n\r\nPrefer to cheer from the sidelines Join other members of the Dal community in front of the Architecture building ', 'Architecture building 2410 Spring Garden Road', 159),
('Wandering the Garden Path linear and areal structures from discrete least cost paths', 'Lectures Seminars', '02:00 PM', '2015-07-27', 'Natural phenomena such as trees clouds and mountains have a richness that computer graphics struggles to replicate. Procedural modeling and texturing have long been used to produce detailed synthetic structures. I will describe an approach to natural phenomena synthesis that uses an irregular graph as the basic building block with an initially random placement of nodes and assignment of node attributes complex structures can be constructed algorithmically.', 'Slonim Room 430 Goldberg Computer Science Building', 160),
('Connecting the Dots Confronting Environmental Racism in Nova Scotia', 'Community Interest', '06:00 PM', '2015-07-28', 'This event is based on a research study being conducted by Dr. Ingrid Waldron in the School of Nursing at Dalhousie. It will feature Mikmaw and African Nova Scotian activists as well as MLA Lenore Zann who will be discussing environmental racism in Nova Scotia. The activists will be discussing their challenges successes and strategies for mobilizing on environmental racism in the province. ', 'Halifax Central Library Paul ORegan Hall', 161),
('Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology M.Sc. Thesis Defence', 'Lectures Seminars', '09:30 AM', NULL, 'The Faculty of Graduate Studies wishes to announce Matthew L. Harty MSc candidate will be defending his thesis entitled Studying the Role of the Divalent Metal Cation Activator of the Cambialistic Enzyme Mandelate Racemase on July 28th at 9:30 a.m.', 'Room 1116 McCain Building', 162),
('PhD Defence Department Of Microbiology & Immunology', 'Lectures Seminars', '09:00 AM', '2015-07-29', 'The Faculty of Graduate Studies wishes to announce Drew Slauenwhite PhD candidate from the Department of Microbiology & Immunology will be defending his thesis entitled The Functional Characterization of Invariant Natural Killer T Cells and the Chemokine Receptor Cxcr6 in a Mouse Model Of Inflammatory Arthritis on Wednesday', 'Room CS 430 The Goldberg Computer Science Building 6050 University Avenue', 163),
('Two phased Optimization Approach for Scheduling Project in a Machine Shop', 'Lectures Seminars', '12:00 PM ', '2015-07-29', 'project based on a real-life case study looks at the job shop scheduling problem from a project planning and scheduling perspective. In the job-shop in question every client customer order is considered as a project with a batch of parts. \r\nWe propose a hierarchical production planning approach to scheduling production. First a planning model produce a long-term plan for the production considering promised due-dates. Then the result from the planning model is used in the scheduling model to provide a short-term schedule for the production whose objective is to minimize total weighted tardiness.', 'MA310', 164),
('Biochemistry and Molecular Biology And Comparative Genomics and Evolutionary Bioinformatics', 'Lectures Seminars', '04:00 PM', '2015-07-30', 'Dr. Thomas Richards a Professor of Evolutionary Genomics at the University of Exeter will deliver a lecture titled Horizontal gene transfer and the evolution of osmotrophic phenotypes. All are welcome.', 'Room 3H1 Sir Charles Tupper Medical Building', 165),
('CGEB Dept Seminar Dr.Thomas Richards', 'Lectures Seminars', '04:00 PM', '2015-07-30', 'Seminar sponsored by Center for Comparative Genomics & Evolutionary Bioinformatics and Dept. of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology \r\nSpeaker Dr. Thomas Richards Prof. of Evolutionary Genomics University of Exeter \r\nTitle Horizontal gene transfer and the evolution of osmotrophic phenotypes', 'Sir Charles Tupper Medical Building Room 3H1', 166);
