('INFRASTRUCTURE FUNDING WILL PUT DAL ON THE MAP FOR RARE DISEASE RESEARCH', 'With today equipment we can diagnose genes that cause a rare disease within a week and with less cost explains Dr. Chris McMaster the Carnegie and Rockefeller Professor and head of the Department of Pharmacology at Dalhousie Medical School. Before it used to take 5-7 years to make a diagnosis.\r\n', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/01/infrastructure-funding-will-put-dal-on-the-map-for-rare-disease-.html', '2015-06-01', 'Research, Pharmacology', 121, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/01/infrastructure-funding-will-put-dal-on-the-map-for-rare-disease-/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1433160799526.jpg'),
('PRIVATE DONORS ENHANCE MELANOMA CARE IN THE MARITIMES', 'Melanoma diagnoses are on the rise across the nation. According to the Public Health Agency of Canada, one in 59 men and one in 73 women could develop melanoma in their lifetime. Its the most serious type of skin cancer.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/03/private-donors-enhance-melanoma-care-in-the-maritimes.html', '2015-06-03', 'News', 122, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/03/private-donors-enhance-melanoma-care-in-the-maritimes/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1433333452424.jpg'),
('THE LITTLE THINGS THAT MAKE A BIG DIFFERENCE', 'Talk to any of the the nearly 3000 graduates who crossed the stage at Spring Convocation ceremonies this year and they would likely have a story about a Dal staff or faculty member who helped them in a time of need. Perhaps that need was small: a document that needed signed a university process that was unclear or a tiny concern that benefited from simply being heard.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/04/the-little-things-that-make-a-big-difference--rosemary-gill-awar.html', '2015-06-04', 'Arts and Social Sciences', 123, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/04/the-little-things-that-make-a-big-difference--rosemary-gill-awar/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1433449666560.jpg'),
('WORDS OF WISDOM INSIGHTS FROM DALS NEWEST HONORARY DEGREE RECIPIENTS', 'An honorary doctorate is the highest honour that Dalhousie can bestow on an individual. It recognizes a lifetime of achievement community impact scholarship and contribution to society. The diversity of experiences of the 10 individuals honoured at Spring Convocation reflect this wide breadth of accomplishment.  ', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/04/words-of-wisdom--insights-from-dal-s-honorary-degree-recipients.html', '2015-06-04', 'Convocation', 124, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/04/words-of-wisdom--insights-from-dal-s-honorary-degree-recipients/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1433418069935.jpg'),
('STUDYING BLACK CANADIAN LEADERSHIP', 'The occasion was the second biennial Black Canadian Studies Association conference hosted at Dalhousie by the James R. Johnston Chair in Black Canadian Studies. The event welcomed participants from across Canada and from as far away as Germany and the United Kingdom.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/05/studying-black-canadian-leadership.html', '2015-06-05', 'Research', 125, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/05/studying-black-canadian-leadership/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1433448160529.jpg'),
('DAL BEGINS WORK TO IMPLEMENT BELONG RECOMMENDATIONS', 'Outlined initially as part of the universitys Strategic Direction last year but accelerated in light of events in the Faculty of Dentistry the initiative aims to ensure a collegial culture at Dalhousie for faculty staff and students one that celebrates diversity and ensures that all members of the Dal community feel included.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/05/dal-begins-work-to-implement--belong--recommendations.html', '2015-06-05', 'News', 126, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/05/dal-begins-work-to-implement--belong--recommendations/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1433444248790.jpg'),
('MAKING WAVES A SURVEY OF OCEANS RESEARCH AT DAL', 'The oceans cover approximately 70 per cent of the earth surface. Whether or not we know it we all depend on the ocean. The ocean helps produce the oxygen we breathe acts as a major transportation route for goods is a major supplier of food and is a favourite place of outdoor enthusiasts.  ', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/08/making-waves--a-survey-of-oceans-research-at-dal.html', '2015-06-08', 'Research', 127, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/08/making-waves--a-survey-of-oceans-research-at-dal/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1434053374331.jpg'),
('KNOWLEDGE IS OCEAN POWER INCREASING OCEAN LITERACY AMONG YOUTH IN NOVA SCOTIA', 'Three Dalhousie researchers set out to study the level of ocean literacy in Nova Scotian students and their findings offer a glimpse into provincial school curriculum and how youth in the province understand the ocean today. With ever increasing human dependence on the oceans and concerns over climate change and human activities that threaten the health of the world oceans researchers believe it is crucial that citizens become more educated and informed about their ocean environment.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/08/knowledge-is-ocean-power--increasing-ocean-literacy-among-youth-.html', '2015-06-08', 'Research', 128, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/08/knowledge-is-ocean-power--increasing-ocean-literacy-among-youth-/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1433770870050.jpg'),
('A PARTNERSHIP IN HANDS ON LEARNING', 'The annual trip takes students out of the classroom and into the field travelling to western Nevada and eastern California for month-long learning experiences. Rachel Milligan who graduated in 2014 with her BSC in Earth Sciences with first class honours attended the field school twice once as a student and once as a teaching assistant. She says it was perhaps the highlight of her time at Dal.\r\n', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/08/a-partnership-in-hands-on-learning.html', '2015-06-08', 'Earth Sciences', 129, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/08/a-partnership-in-hands-on-learning/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1433777671444.jpg'),
('MEET NEW DSU PRESIDENT DAN NICHOLSON', 'Although the new DSU executive has held office for only a few weeks now Nicholson says there are already so many things on the go first and foremost the upcoming Student Union Building renovations.\r\n\r\nThe energy around this project has been absolutely incredible says Nicholson a Neuroscience student at Dal.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/10/meet-new-dsu-president-dan-nicholson.html', '2015-06-10', 'Studentlife', 130, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/10/meet-new-dsu-president-dan-nicholson/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1433860992462.jpg'),
('RESEARCH THAT HELPS COMPANIES GROW', 'Industry collaborations, from partnerships with local start-ups to projects with large multinationals are a key pillar to research happening at Dal. Dal Industry Liaison and Innovation office facilitates these collaborations. The results of relationships with industry are widespread benefiting Dal researchers and students advancing industry and helping to drive the economy.\r\n', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/11/research-that-helps-companies-grow.html', '2015-06-11', 'Engineering', 131, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/11/research-that-helps-companies-grow/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1434053505967.jpg'),
('BLUE FRONTIER', 'The oceans are a precious resource essential not only to humanity but also to the function of our planet. What role can a university play in developing marine science technology and management in support of prosperous and sustainable human-ocean relations That was the question at the core of a presentation by Dalhousie President Richard Florizone and co-authored by Professor Emeritus John Cullen at the Beijing Forum 2014 in November. Here we provide a snapshot of their thoughts on how Dal can help develop the nascent blue economy—responsibly and sustainably—and why both pure and applied research are essential to that effort.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/12/bluefrontier.html', '2015-06-12', 'Research', 132, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/12/bluefrontier/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1434034810540.jpg'),
('SUCCESS IN FAILURE', 'The competition led by Dal grad Peter Braithwaite and guest engineer William Loasby of Fast and Epp Structural Engineers begins with students submitting models of their current design projects for consideration. Instructors then identify five student designs out of the 60 or so submissions to be developed for testing on a larger scale. Some designs are chosen because of their robustness others because of their sense of adventure. Arches bridge structures and traditional frame structures are all in play.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/12/success-in-failure.html', '2015-06-12', 'Studentlife', 133, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/12/success-in-failure/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1434053433021.jpg'),
('IMPROVING DAL AS A WORKPLACE', 'Dalhousie faculty and staff take pride in their work and believe their contributions are valued. But they also have concerns about workload stress and opportunities for career advancement.\r\n\r\nThose are just a few quick snapshots from the 2015 edition of Dalhousie employee survey the results of which were released this week. Every two years the university asks faculty and staff about their work their view of their job their workload their relationships and the university as a workplace more generally.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/15/improving-dal-as-a-workplace.html', '2015-06-15', 'News', 134, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/15/improving-dal-as-a-workplace/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1434367471883.jpg'),
('OPENING DOORS AND MINDS AT THE STEELE OCEAN SCIENCES BUILDING', 'What does carbon dioxide do to the ocean. How do baleen whales feed. Is the Aquatron the name of a character from the next Transformers movie. These questions and many more were answered at the Steele Ocean Sciences Building during this year Doors Open Halifax.\r\n\r\nEach year the citywide event puts out the welcome mat for many of the Halifax historical or architecturally significant buildings allowing the public to tour the spaces throughout the weekend.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/16/opening-doors-and-minds-at-the-steele-ocean-sciences-building.html', '2015-06-16', 'Biology', 135, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/16/opening-doors-and-minds-at-the-steele-ocean-sciences-building/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1434455392588.jpg'),
('PHOTO ESSAY DOORS OPEN AT DAL', 'On June 6 and 7 more than 1400 visitors stopped by Dalhousie Steele Ocean Sciences Building during Doors Open Halifax. It was the second year the building was included in the annual event and it has quickly become a popular attraction thanks to its combination of hands on science experiences with family friendly activities.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/16/photo-essay--doors-open-at-dal.html', '2015-06-16', 'Biology', 136, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/16/photo-essay--doors-open-at-dal/_jcr_content/contentPar/dalphotogallery/featureSlider/featureslide/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1434395406935.jpg'),
('CELEBRATION AND GOOD CHEER AT DAL ANNUAL RETIREES TEA', 'The winding down of a long successful Dalhousie career is an opportunity for reflection celebration and good cheer.\r\n\r\nAll were in abundance at this year Retirees Tea which took place last Thursday June 12 at the President House. The annual event recognizes faculty and staff who have retired from the university within the past year.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/17/celebration-and-good-cheer-at-dal-s-annual-retirees-tea.html', '2015-06-17', 'Senior Administration', 137, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/17/celebration-and-good-cheer-at-dal-s-annual-retirees-tea/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1434546390098.jpg'),
('CHARGING ONWARD: DAHN NEXT MOVE MARKS FIRST CANADIAN UNIVERSITY COLLABORATION WITH TESLA MOTORS', 'When a Tesla Model S electric vehicle made an appearance at Dalhousie University yesterday its near silent engine sound and sleek design prompted a symphony of ohs and ahs from impressed onlookers. But it was a brand new partnership between Tesla Motors and Dalhousie University that got members of the Dalhousie research community really excited. ', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/17/charging-onward--dahns-next-move-marks-first-canadian-university.html', '2015-06-17', 'News', 138, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/17/charging-onward--dahns-next-move-marks-first-canadian-university/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1434654287788.jpg'),
('MARKING MILESTONES', 'Dalhousie is a community that changes all the time students graduate new students arrive and faculty/staff move through the university. Indeed sometimes all it takes is a few years or even a few moments for someone to make an impact that resonates.\r\n\r\nBut across the university are individuals who have spent a good portion of their live as part of the Dalhousie community making a difference day-in and day-out in the lives of students faculty and staff. Last Friday Dalhousie celebrated some of those individuals who within the past year reached key milestones in their Dalhousie stories 25 35 and 45 years served. Each received their special commemorative pin.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/18/marking-milestones.html', '2015-06-18', 'Human Resources', 139, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/18/marking-milestones/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1434467809174.jpg'),
('A MYSTERY UNRAVELLED', 'Margaret Cameron president of Dalhousie Alumni Association Women Division is selfadmittedly curious by nature. I love to ask questions she says with a smile. And it was her curiosity that led to the unravelling of a 100 year old mystery.\r\n\r\nEstablished in 1909 the Women Division has for many years been financially supported by the Emily Bevan Harrington Fund. In 2012 Cameron headed to the Dal archives to find out just who Emily Bevan Harrington was. I had assumed that she was a wealthy woman who left her estate to Dalhousie says Cameron. I would soon find out that was not the case at all.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/19/a-mystery-unravelled.html', '2015-06-19', 'Alumni', 140, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/19/a-mystery-unravelled/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1434471018396.jpg'),
('DALHOUSIE RESEARCHERS RECEIVE FUNDING TO FURTHER DISCOVERIES', 'Fifty-four researchers from five of Dal Faculties Agriculture Computer Sciences Engineering Health Professions and Science were recognized on Monday for their creative and innovative approaches to research.\r\n\r\nEd Holder minister of state announced the recipients of the Natural Sciences and Engineering Research Council Discovery Grants Program at the University of Ontario Institute of Technology in Oshawa Ontario.\r\n', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/23/dalhousie-researchers-receive-funding-to-further-discoveries.html', '2015-06-23', 'Health and Human Performance', 141, 'http://www.dal.ca/content/dam/dalhousie/images/dalnews/2015/June/heather-210.jpg'),
('OUT WITH THE OLD IN WITH THE NEW', 'With companies and organizations around the world looking for alternatives to traditional fossil fuels one researcher at Dal Faculty of Agriculture is looking at new ways to change how fuels are produced using environmentally sustainable and readily available methods.\r\n\r\nSophia He is a chemical engineer on the Dalhousie Agricultural Campus. For more than 20 years Dr. He has been working on reaction and separation engineering. More recently she been focusing on biofuels and bio product development.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/23/out-with-the-old--in-with-the-new.html', '2015-06-23', 'Agriculture', 142, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/23/out-with-the-old--in-with-the-new/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1435062445012.jpg'),
('REFLECTION AND FOCUS PRESIDENT FLORIZONE OFFERS YEAR IN REVIEW', 'Partway through a presentation that offered many facts and figures for the audience in Ondaatje Hall Dalhousie President Richard Florizone paused to place the statistics in context.\r\n\r\nThis all comes back to people said President Florizone. We cannot achieve the mission of the university without our people.\r\n\r\nIt was a message he would return to throughout the 1.5-hour session held this week under the banner of Inspiration and Impact Our First Year.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/24/reflection-and-focus--president-florizone-offers-year-in-review.html', '2015-06-24', 'News', 143, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/24/reflection-and-focus--president-florizone-offers-year-in-review/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1435143595918.jpg'),
('CELEBRATING DAL TOP TEACHERS', 'The recipients announced earlier this month at Senate are more plentiful than in the past. That because last year Senate approved an expanded suite of teaching awards to increase teaching recognition inside and outside the Dal community and encourage continued excellence in pedagogy. This included four new awards for early-career faculty for graduate supervision for academic innovation and for excellence in diversity education.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/25/celebrating-dal-s-top-teachers.html', '2015-06-25', 'Commerce', 144, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/25/celebrating-dal-s-top-teachers/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1435234367430.jpg'),
('THE NEXT PHASE IN E?LEARNING AT DAL', 'E-learning is transforming several aspects of higher education. Using technologies to support in-class online and blended approaches to teaching offers some noted advantages to both instructor and learner. These include the opportunity to flip instructional modes especially in large classes in order to enable many more conversations between and among instructors and students.\r\n', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/25/the-next-phase-in-e-learning-at-dal.html', '2015-06-25', 'Libraries', 145, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/25/the-next-phase-in-e-learning-at-dal/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1435235998567.jpg'),
('BOARD OF GOVERNORS HOLDS YEAR END MEETING', 'At the meeting the Board approved the university operating budget for the upcoming year the features of which were communicated to the Dal community through the annual consultation process. Balanced with revenues and expenditures of 398.6 million the budget includes a 1 per cent increase in the provincial operating grant a 3 per cent increase in tuition for all programs a provision for annual salary benefit and pension contribution adjustments for faculty and staff 2.7 million for strategic initiatives nearly 700000 more for student assistance base reductions to faculties and service units totaling 6.7 million and the use of $1.8 million in one-time reserve funds.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/26/board-of-governors-holds-year-end-meeting.html', '2015-06-26', 'News', 146, ''),
('HEAD HANDS HEALTH AND A WHOLE LOT OF HEART', 'To say Breagh Ross is involved with her school and her community would be an understatement.\r\n\r\nHer countless hours dedicated to extracurricular activities on the agricultural campus and her time spent training and practicing for 4-H competitions did not go unnoticed. For Breagh her accomplishments are no small feat considering she does not even have a background in farming.\r\n', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/01/head--hands--health-and-a-whole-lot-of-heart.html', '2015-05-01', 'Science', 150, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/01/head--hands--health-and-a-whole-lot-of-heart/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1430403247640.jpg'),
('UNDERSTANDING THE UNSEEN', 'The base of the ocean food chain is comprised of a network of microscopic marine machines capable of converting greenhouse gasses into life-sustaining oxygen. These microbes while invisible to the naked eye are extremely important not only to life under the ocean but to life above it too.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/26/understanding-the-unseen.html', '2015-06-26', 'Research', 147, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/26/understanding-the-unseen/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1435260450640.jpg'),
('A BLOOMIN GOOD TIME', 'What screams summer more than some time in the garden At Boots n Blooms Dal faculty staff and friends put their green thumbs to work helping grounds crews get campus ready for the summer months. A tradition that started on the Agricultural Campus last year Boots n Blooms expanded to the Halifax campuses as well. This year events took place on June 19 and June 25 and we sent Nick Pearce and Stephanie Rogers respectively to capture the sights.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/29/a-bloomin--good-time.html', '2015-06-26', 'Research', 148, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/29/a-bloomin--good-time/_jcr_content/contentPar/dalphotogallery/featureSlider/featureslide/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1435330027652.jpg'),
('INSPIRATION AND IMPACT VIDEO HIGHLIGHTS', 'Last week during his presentation at the Inspiration and Impact Our First Year events President Richard Florizone shared five video clips demonstrating how Dalhousies students faculty and staff bring the universitys Strategic Direction to life.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/06/30/inspiration-and-impact--video-highlights.html', '2015-06-30', 'News', 149, ''),
('BUILDING COMMUNITY', 'You only have to look at Pickard impressive résumé to confirm that he shares his mentors dedication to community engagement and building. In fact many of the projects he has been involved with have been Dalhousie-related initiatives. Some were done through Dalhousie Cities and Environment Unit while others came about through his participation as both an instructor and student in the School of Architecture one-of-a-kind design and build Free Lab course work.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/04/building-community.html', '2015-07-04', 'Architecture', 151, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/04/building-community/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1431029050211.jpg'),
('CHEERS FOR THE CHANCELLOR', 'Fred Fountain is a name that Dalhousie knows well. His family name adorns one of the houses Halifax Howe Hall residence as well as Dalhousie School of Performing Arts. His family is a generous donor to the university and the donation to establish the Fountain School is the largest in the history of Dal Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/06/cheers-for-a-chancellor.html', '2015-07-05', 'Arts and Social Sciences', 152, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/06/cheers-for-a-chancellor/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1431029188167.jpg'),
('NEW EQUIPMENT NEW POSSIBILITIES', 'Dalhousie Faculty of Agriculture and CASE IH a global leader in agricultural equipment have entered into a new five-plus-five agreement. The Faculty will have the use of about 16 pieces of CASE IH equipment each year for the next five years with the commitment to renew for another five years and beyond. The leading-edge farm machinery will be used for teaching production and research.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/06/new-equipment--new-possibilities.html', '2015-05-06', 'Agriculture', 153, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/06/new-equipment--new-possibilities/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1431029093866.jpg'),
('GET OUTSIDE DAL SIGNS UP FOR NATURE CHALLENGE', 'The challenge is simple: spend 30 minutes a day outside for each of the month 30 days. The idea is to encourage people to take time away from their desks and daily tasks and enjoy the outdoors. The overall 30 x 30 initiative launched by the David Suzuki Foundation focuses on engagement with nature but Daniel Rainham the Elizabeth May Chair says the challenge is also about encouraging healthier lifestyles.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/07/get-outside--dal-signs-up-for-may-nature-challenge.html', '2015-05-07', 'News', 154, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/07/get-outside--dal-signs-up-for-may-nature-challenge/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1430995952312.jpg'),
('DALHOUSIE SPORT HALL OF FAME INDUCTS NEW MEMBERS', 'Former Dalhousie student and CBC broadcaster Bruce Rainnie served as Master of Ceremonies for the event. This year class of inductees featured football player Robert Lewington who played four season with the Tigers from 1966-70. Dr. Carolyn Savoy who spent more than 30 years here at Dalhousie as a faculty member and the coach of the women basketball team was inducted posthumously while 11 members of the 1995 men soccer team who won a national gold medal were on hand to be inducted as a team.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/08/dalhousie-sport-hall-of-fame-induction.html', '2015-07-08', 'Sports', 155, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/08/dalhousie-sport-hall-of-fame-induction/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1431623332681.jpg'),
('AN INTEREST IN FOOD TAKES ROOT', 'After completing an undergraduate degree in History she sought an opportunity to pursue her interest academically. I had been thinking about studying food in some way she explains and I hadn found the place I could do that in the way that I wanted to. Angela heard about SRES and began the MES program as a part-time student.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/08/an-interest-in-food-takes-root.html', '2015-05-08', 'News', 156, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/08/an-interest-in-food-takes-root/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1431028636198.jpg'),
('DAL RESEARCHERS IDENTIFY CELL CHANGING GENE THAT CAN CAUSE CANCER', 'There are eight known human herpes viruses all capable of establishing life-long infection. The most recently discovered of these viruses herpesvirus-8 is the cause of several AIDS-related cancers including a form of skin cancer known as Kaposi sarcoma.\r\n\r\nHerpesvirus-8 targets cells that line the surface of blood and lymphatic vessels. The virus reprograms these cells giving them instructions to grow form new vessels and inflame surrounding tissues. These changes in the cells can lead to malignancies.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/12/dal-researchers-identify-cellchanging-gene-that-can-cause-cancer.html', '2015-05-12', 'Research', 157, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/12/dal-researchers-identify-cellchanging-gene-that-can-cause-cancer/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1431371008834.jpg'),
('EXTINCTION HOTSPOTS HOW THE FOSSILIZED PAST CAN HELP PREDICT OUR OCEANS FUTURE', 'Dal researchers Heike Lotze and Derek Tittensor both of the Department of Biology joined a international team of ecologists and paleontologists to study fossil records from the past 23 million years — the time period most closely resembling Earth today — and combined that data with what we know about the present state of our oceans. The study was published in Science on May 1.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/13/hotspots--how-extinctions-past-can-help-predict-the-future-of-ou.html', '2015-05-13', 'Research', 158, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/13/hotspots--how-extinctions-past-can-help-predict-the-future-of-ou/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1431448293655.jpg'),
('SCIENCE SUPERSTARS SHOW OFF THEIR STUFF', 'The occasion is the sixth-annual Let Talk Science Challenge at Dalhousie which brings together students from grades 6-8 to engage in learning about the sciences. Run largely by volunteers with the Dalhousie chapter of Let Talk Science the event involved a three-part competition  two sections of Science Quiz Show followed by the design challenge.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/14/science-superstars-show-off-their-stuff.html', '2015-05-14', 'Science', 159, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/14/science-superstars-show-off-their-stuff/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1431623172725.jpg'),
('SALUTING SUSTAINABILITY SUCCESSES', 'The first order of business was a matter of national recognition: earlier this year STARS awarded Dalhousie a gold ranking this year up from the silver Dal received in 2011. The elements that contributed to that upgrade included the new use of mini-trucks around campus the academic course simply called bike Dal TREEHouse AC and the biomass replacement initiative among many others.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/15/saluting-sustainability-successes.html', '2015-05-15', 'Facilities Management', 160, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/15/saluting-sustainability-successes/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1431618375921.jpg'),
('ENCOURAGING YOUTH ORAL HEALTH IN SOUTHEAST LABRADOR', 'Earlier this year members of the Faculties of Health Professions and Dentistry came together to present Oral Health and Indigenous Youth: A Forum for Community Members Researchers and Policy-Makers. Following a three-year research project funded by the Canadian Institutes of Health Research the event was a culmination of findings to demonstrate the state of oral health in NunatuKavut and develop a plan for the future.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/20/encouraging-youth-oral-health-in-southeast-labrador.html', '2015-05-20', 'Research', 161, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/20/encouraging-youth-oral-health-in-southeast-labrador/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1432232034138.jpg'),
('CONGRATS TO THE CLASS OF 2015', 'It is that time of year again: Spring Convocation began with the Faculty of Agriculture ceremony on Friday May 8 and continues May 25-30 in Halifax. Congrats to all of Dal newest graduates as they set out to make their mark on the world!\r\n\r\nTwice each year at Spring and Fall Convocation Dalhousie publishes a Convocation Keepsake with profiles of some of our stellar graduates. We also publish these profiles here on Dal News. For more information', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/25/congrats-to-the-class-of-2015-.html', '2015-05-25', 'Convocation', 162, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/25/congrats-to-the-class-of-2015-/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1432835750018.jpg'),
('UP TO THE CHALLENGE', 'Growing up in Ottawa Ont. Brittany wanted to branch out so she set her sights on Dalhousie where she is graduating with a Bachelor of Arts with an Honours in Social Anthropology and a minor in French. During her degree she had the opportunity to work as a student assistant for the Department of Political Science had a paper published in Pangaea the Undergraduate History Society journal and volunteered as a tutor with the national literacy organization Frontier College.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/25/up-to-the-challenge.html', '2015-05-26', 'News', 163, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/25/up-to-the-challenge/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1432835127471.jpg'),
('MANAGING MULTIPLE CULTURES', 'Lokiy originally from Jining City in China Shandong Province researched universities worldwide but in the end only applied to one. I was interested in Canada because it so diverse and safe and chose Dal because of its reputation commerce co-op program and location. Halifax is a small safe city on the ocean and the people are so friendly.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/26/managing-multiple-cultures.html', '2015-05-27', 'Commerce ', 164, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/26/managing-multiple-cultures/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1432644387461.jpg'),
('FROM FAR TO HERE INTERNATIONAL GRADS ON THEIR DAL EXPERIENCES AND NEXT STEPS', 'Among the hundreds of graduates crossing the stage at Spring Convocation ceremonies this month are students whose path to Dal started in countries around the world. And while their journeys ahead may well be equally as vast in the distance they span many are planning to stay — in Nova Scotia in the Maritimes in Canada. Here a look at just a few of those students and their stories.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/28/from-far-to-here--international-grads-on-their-dal-experiences-a.html', '2015-05-28', 'International', 165, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/28/from-far-to-here--international-grads-on-their-dal-experiences-a/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1432823603825.jpg'),
('WASTE NOT WANT NOT', 'Earlier this year Rob was honoured with the Camp 7 Iron Ring Award which recognizes a graduating Engineering student who displays an exceptionally high professional attitude. The award is a credit to his academic record but also to his work with Engineers Without Borders (EWB). School can only teach you so much he says. You have to make sure you get involved outside the classroom too.\r\n', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/29/waste-not--want-not.html', '2015-05-29', 'Environmental Engineering ', 166, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/29/waste-not--want-not/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1432833396337.jpg'),
('PRESCRIBED A CAREER IN MEDICINE', 'Now graduating with a Doctor of Medicine degree Luke is enthusiastic about starting his residency in emergency medicine. One of the things I really like about medicine is helping people. I enjoy the positive impact you can have on a person and their community.\r\n\r\nLuke desire to help others is evident. He regularly volunteers at Making Waves a swimming program for children with disabilities and Camp Triumph a summer camp for children with chronic illness in their family.  ', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/29/prescribed-a-career-in-medicine.html', '2015-05-30', 'Medicine', 167, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/29/prescribed-a-career-in-medicine/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1432833742185.jpg'),
('ALL SMILES', 'Amanda Lee has always been a people person with an interest in health care but she did not always know where and how the two would intersect.\r\n\r\nAfter two years in an applied human nutrition program she found herself wanting something more hands on so she welcomed an opportunity to spend a day shadowing a dental hygienist.\r\n\r\nThe hygienist had a way about her that made the patient feel like she was not even in the dental chair recalls Amanda. It was something I could see myself doing.', 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/29/something-to-smile-about.html', '2015-05-31', 'Dentistry', 168, 'http://www.dal.ca/news/2015/05/29/something-to-smile-about/_jcr_content/image.adaptive.579.high.jpg/1432834153497.jpg');
